title: A handwriting tool which organizes the drawing in a tree structure
title_en: A handwriting tool which organizes the drawing in a tree structure
abstract: 本研究は講義や議論で行われる手書き描画を対象に、ストローク集合をノードとして階層的に整理することで描画の効率化と描画間の論理関係の可視化を図る手法を提案する。 本研究は各ノードをストローク集合として表現し、子ノード間の共通ストロークを抽出して親ノードを生成する方式と、ツリー構造を明示的に扱う作成・閲覧・編集用インタフェースを実装して評価した。
abstract_en: This research proposes a method that organizes handwritten drawings from lectures and discussions into a hierarchy by treating stroke sets as nodes to improve drawing efficiency and visualize logical relations between drawings. This research represents each node as a set of strokes, extracts common strokes between child nodes to create parent nodes, and implements an interface for explicit creation, viewing, and editing of the tree structure for evaluation.
positioning_summary: 本研究は手書き描画をストローク集合でノード化して階層的に整理することで描画効率と描画間の論理関係の可視化を目指す研究である。 本研究は講義や議論での紙・黒板・デジタルインクによる手書き描画を対象に、既存の作成・閲覧・編集支援が不足している点を埋めることを目標としている。
positioning_summary_en: This research aims to improve drawing efficiency and visualize logical relations between drawings by organizing handwritten drawings into a hierarchy of stroke-set nodes. This research targets handwritten drawings in lectures and discussions on paper, blackboards, and digital ink, aiming to fill gaps in existing creation, viewing, and editing support.
purpose_summary: 本研究は手書き図が構造化されておらず編集や検索が困難であるという問題を解決することを目的としている。 本研究はノート作成を行う手書き利用者の作業負担軽減を目標に、ストローク間の共通性抽出で親ノードを構成する方式を用いることを目的としている。
purpose_summary_en: This study aims to solve the problem that handwritten diagrams are unstructured and therefore difficult to edit and search. This study aims to reduce the workload of handwritten note users by using a method that constructs parent nodes through extraction of commonality among strokes.
method_summary: 本システムは各ノードをストローク集合として表現し、ツリー構造上で描画要素を親子関係で組織化する方式を採用している。 本システムは2つの子ノード間の共通ストロークを抽出して親ノードを構築するアルゴリズムと、ツリーを明示的に扱う作成・閲覧・編集用GUIを実装して既存描画ツールとの連携を図っている。
method_summary_en: The system represents each node as a set of strokes and organizes drawing elements into parent-child relationships in a tree structure. The system implements an algorithm that extracts common strokes between two child nodes to form a parent node and provides a GUI for explicit creation, viewing, and editing of the tree while integrating with existing drawing tools.
evaluation_summary: 本研究はプロトタイプを用いて「利用経験の評価」と「ノート取りのユーザーテスト」の2種類の方法で評価を行った。 本研究は既存のデジタル手書きツールとの比較評価の結果から自動ノード追加機能とノードサムネイル提示方法の改善が必要であると結論づけ、抜粋では参加者数や定量的指標の詳細は示されていないと報告している。
evaluation_summary_en: The research evaluated a prototype using two methods: an evaluation of user experience and a user test of note-taking. The research concluded from comparisons with existing digital handwriting tools that improvements are needed in automatic node addition and node thumbnail presentation, and the excerpt reports that details such as participant numbers and quantitative metrics are not provided.

Title: A handwriting tool which organizes the drawing in a tree structure
Authors: Hideto Takei, Minoru Terada
Year: 2006
Abstract: This research proposes a method that organizes handwritten drawings from lectures and discussions into a hierarchy by treating stroke sets as nodes to improve drawing efficiency and visualize logical relations between drawings. This research represents each node as a set of strokes, extracts common strokes between child nodes to create parent nodes, and implements an interface for explicit creation, viewing, and editing of the tree structure for evaluation.
Positioning Summary: This research aims to improve drawing efficiency and visualize logical relations between drawings by organizing handwritten drawings into a hierarchy of stroke-set nodes. This research targets handwritten drawings in lectures and discussions on paper, blackboards, and digital ink, aiming to fill gaps in existing creation, viewing, and editing support.
Purpose Summary: This study aims to solve the problem that handwritten diagrams are unstructured and therefore difficult to edit and search. This study aims to reduce the workload of handwritten note users by using a method that constructs parent nodes through extraction of commonality among strokes.
Method Summary: The system represents each node as a set of strokes and organizes drawing elements into parent-child relationships in a tree structure. The system implements an algorithm that extracts common strokes between two child nodes to form a parent node and provides a GUI for explicit creation, viewing, and editing of the tree while integrating with existing drawing tools.
Evaluation Summary: The research evaluated a prototype using two methods: an evaluation of user experience and a user test of note-taking. The research concluded from comparisons with existing digital handwriting tools that improvements are needed in automatic node addition and node thumbnail presentation, and the excerpt reports that details such as participant numbers and quantitative metrics are not provided.
